SALTBot: Linking Soware and Articles in Wikidata
Jorge Bolinches
1
, Daniel Garijo
1
1
Ontology Engineering Group, Universidad Politcnica de Madrid
Abstract
Research Soware is becoming a recognized rst class citizen to support and reproduce the results of
scientic investigations. However, the link between soware and their corresponding articles is oen
absent from Knowledge Graphs like Wikidata, thus making it challenging to retrieve implementations of
existing papers. In this work we introduce the Soware and Article Linker Toolbot (SALTBot), a bot
for linking together GitHub code repositories with their corresponding scholarly articles in Wikidata
based on their available citation information. In addition, SALTbot will automatically describe soware
entities with metadata. We have manually validated SALTbot in 500 code repositories with citation les,
adding more than 30 new tools to the Wikidata Knowledge Graph.
Paper type: Resource
Code repository: https://github.com/SoftwareUnderstanding/SALTbot

1. Introduction
Research Soware refers to the scripts, tools or computational pipelines developed throughout
an investigation to support the main ndings described in a scientic publication [
1
]. Research
Soware is becoming increasingly recognized as a research product,
1
and the scientic commu-
nity has developed soware citation principles [
2
] and citation formats [
3
] in order to recognize
developers with the appropriate credit.
However, in most existing scholarly Knowledge Graphs to date (e.g., Open Alex [
4
], Wiki-
data [
5
], etc.) research soware are not usually linked with their corresponding publications.
This leads to three main problems: 1) lack of tool context, as articles usually complement
research soware with theoretical background, purpose and experimental results; 2) paper-
implementation availability, as it becomes challenging to know which research papers include
soware for others to reuse; 3) author-developer credit, as some developers may have con-
tributed to a soware tool but not to its associated publication.
In this work, we address these issues by presenting SALTbot, a Soware and Article Linker
Toolbot, designed to nd article and soware entities in Wikibase instances in order to enrich
and link them together. SALTbot takes as input one or multiple GitHub repositories and inspects
them for references to existing articles in Wikidata. Then, if found, SALTbot will link soware
and their corresponding articles, creating a new soware instance when necessary and enriching
it with metadata. Our work includes two main contributions:
